India Equity Movers: Autoline Industries, GTL, Indiabulls Real

-- B y   A m e y a   K a r v e
-- 
2011-06-21T04:26:10Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-21/india-equity-movers-autoline-industries-gtl-indiabulls-real.html
The following companies had unusual
price changes in  India  trading. Stock symbols are in parentheses
and share prices are as of 9:40 a.m. in Mumbai.  The Bombay Stock Exchange Sensitive Index, or Sensex, rose
30.48 points, or 0.2 percent, to 17,537.11, set for the first
gain in five days. The BSE 200 Index was little changed at
2,180.89.  Autoline Industries Ltd. (AUTOL)   climbed 2.7 percent to
131.55 rupees, set for the steepest gain in two weeks. India’s
Pawan Ruia Group is in talks to acquire the Pune-based auto
parts manufacturer, the Economic Times reported on its website,
citing people it didn’t identify. The deal may value Autoline at
about 2.5 billion rupees ($55.6 million), according to the
report.  Four calls made to Autoline Industries’ Chakan office near
Pune were unanswered. Two calls to Pawan Ruia Group’s office in
Kolkata also went unanswered.  GTL Ltd. (GTS)   jumped 9.6 percent to 140.25 rupees,
headed for the steepest gain since May 2009. The company which
manages telecommunication equipment for mobile-phone companies
said yesterday it may approach the market regulator after
“speculative activity” by domestic investors triggered the
record crash in its stock. Group company  GTL Infrastructure Ltd. (GTLI) 
 also surged 7.4 percent to 18.2 rupees, set for the
biggest advance since January 2010.  Indiabulls Real Estate Ltd. (IBREL)   slid 4.3 percent to
99.85 rupees, bond for the lowest closing price since March
2009. India’s Maharashtra Pollution Control Board has directed
the developer to halt work at a residential project in Mumbai,
according to an e-mailed statement from the company.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Ameya Karve in Mumbai at 
 akarve@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
